As vegetation greenness naturally experience seasonal behavior synchronized with climatic variables, before time series analysis, seasonal pattern should be removed to reduce temporal autocorrelation of time series images. De-seasoning activity was made by using standardized Z score time series to generate standardized anomalies, which is mathematically represented as:Z=EVImean-EVIiEVIδ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Z = \frac{{EVI_{mean} - EVI_{i} }}{{EVI_{\delta } }}$$\end{document}where EVImean is long-term mean EVI, EVIi is EVI at time i, and EVIδ is standard deviation of EVI time series within 17 years. Though there need removal of serial correlation by pre-whitening method for Mann Kendal trend test, based on recommendation provided by Yue and Wang (2002) on the nature of data the analysis was made on standardized anomalies without pre-whitening (Bayazit and Önöz 2008). As MODIS NPP dataset is annual composite and seasonality is accounted during compositing phase, there is no need of de-seasoning operation.

